description:
Vertical-slice audit: src/browser/runLive_emit_artifacts.ts:293-298 wrapBrowserExecutorWithV18Emit does:

  return async (options) => {
    const result = await executor(options);     // ← throws skip everything below
    const outcome = await maybeEmit(options, result, emitOptions, options.log);
    return { ...result, v18Emit: outcome };
  };

If the inner executor throws (Pro-tab not verified, network blip, prompt-before-verification, output_empty, …) maybeEmit is never called, so NO v18 evidence ledger entries, NO provider_result.v1, NO artifact_index update are written for failed runs. The audit-trail therefore only records successes; investigation of the 'why did this run fail' question against the on-disk evidence is impossible.

This is an evidence-completeness gap, not a recovery-contract gap — failures still throw to the caller with their typed error. But the v18 §12 audit trail explicitly contemplates failure-arm evidence (the FSM has failure states with errorCodes specifically so the evidence ledger can carry them post-mortem).

Acceptance: wrapBrowserExecutorWithV18Emit catches inner executor errors, calls maybeEmit with a synthesized failure capture (capturing what was observed: lastSeenState, errorCode, timing), then re-throws so the caller's exception flow is unchanged. The emit outcome reports attempted=true with skippedReason=null and a populated emitError if the synthetic emission itself failed. Regression test pins both arms: successful run → emit fires; throwing run → emit fires with failure capture, then exception propagates.
